english:
  title: Lodging as a Guest at Jabok Temple, East of Yeongwang
  author: Yun Yeohyung
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Dongrim Temple stands east of the provincial city.
    I've cast my weathered traveling bundle here within its walls.
    Ten thousand griefs of wandering tangle like scattered cotton—
    ten years of drifting leave tracks as rootless as tumbleweed.

    Clouds heavy with twilight descend upon the rocky trees,
    while autumn rain taps messages on parasol leaves by the well.

    What use is there for a merchant passing through these lands?
    Years slip away—my temples graying, my purse grown light.
  footnotes:
    - 'Dongrim Temple: A reference to the famous temple in China where the Tang poet Bai Juyi (白居易) once stayed, evoking themes of Buddhist refuge and scholarly retreat.'
    - 'Tumbleweed: A metaphor for aimless wandering without direction or root, contrasting the speaker''s decade of travel with the natural restlessness of the plant.'
    - 'The parasol tree: A traditional image in East Asian poetry symbolizing autumn, melancholy, and the passage of time.'
